    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-09-26T14:05:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-09-26T14:05:00-05:00" n="280"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d280">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <gloss target="#t_FE1">FE</gloss> files, lot 55 D 128: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">President</gloss> to the Commander in
                        Chief, Far East (<persName corresp="#p_CGMW1" type="to"
                        >Clark</persName>)</hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d280fn1">This telegram, marked “personal for <persName
                            corresp="#p_CGMW1">General Clark</persName>,” was sent to the <gloss
                            target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss> and the Secretary of Defense for their
                        information.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret<lb/>operational immediate</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1952-09-26T15:05:00-04:00"
                            >September 26, 1952—3:05 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>262005Z. You have received from the Joint Chiefs of Staff my approval of a course
                    of action to be followed at Panmunjom.<note n="2" xml:id="d280fn2">Reference is
                        to <gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss> 919368, Sept. 25, <ref
                            target="#pg_539">p. 539</ref>.</note> I hope that the initial statement
                    by our delegation can be made in meeting on 28 Sept, that it be presented with
                    the utmost firmness and without subsequent debate, and with insistence that the
                    Communists reply be given at a meeting to be held on or about 8 Oct.</p>
                <p>If this latter meeting does not produce the results we seek it then must be made
                    unmistakably clear to the Communists, first, that having made a firm proposal
                    for a fair and just armistice, we declare an indefinite recess of the meetings;
                    and second, that we are willing to reconvene when and if the Communists express
                    a willingness to accept our proposal. It is essential of course that throughout
                    this coming period the military pressure which you are so effectively applying
                    against the enemy should not be lessened.</p>
            </div>
